This must mean that he was quaestor in the first· mentioned reign, and either tribune or aedile under Titus: while we know that he held the praetorship in an. 88. The next point to be settled, on the theory that Tacitus wrote the Dialoguc, is the date at which it was composed and published. Here the views of the critics diverge, as we have already seen, very considerahly. Many of them have given undue weight to the passage in the Agricola in which Tacitus resers to Domitian's reign as a period during which ‘the young have passed to old age, aoc'th closed lips, and the old almost to the very goal and term oi life ¹.’ From the phrase pcr sc‘lcnlcicm it has been inferred that Tacitus cannot have written anything oi any kind in the reign of Domitian, and the conclusion drawn has been that the Dc'aloguc must have been composed either in the reign ol Titus or else after Domitian’s death, about the same time as the other minor works. But in the passage under consideration, Tacitus is speaking as a historian who (though he may have been industriously collecting material in the evil days which had now come to a close) is hailing a happier era as per· mitting him at length to break the silence into which he had been coerced. It is quite conceivable that, whether published or not at the time of composition, sucha work as the Dc'aloguc might have been written in the earlier and brighter years of Domitian's reign.
